-heading\" data-id=\"7009019\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-e-type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"heading.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<h2 class=\"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default\">Ensure Lasting Pavement with Pothole Repair &amp; Asphalt Patching Across the Southeast<\/h2>\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-b23f66d elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor\" data-id=\"b23f66d\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-e-type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"text-editor.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p>Since these holes start small and quickly affect everything around them, the quicker they\u2019re identified and patched, the less damage they\u2019ll cause. It\u2019s not uncommon for a pothole or two\u2014when left unpatched\u2014to spread and create a costly repair job on a surface that was otherwise in good shape.<\/p><p><span style=\"font-size: 16px; color: var( --e-global-color-accent ); background-color: var( --e-global-color-primary );\">The best time to identify potholes is after a hard rain. Rain can loosen the ground underneath and around a paved surface, causing the ground shift problem. It can also enter small cracks and widen them. Look for standing water in lower areas that are more likely to be affected.<\/span><\/p>\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<\/div>\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-56d5578 elementor-widget elementor-widget-button\" data-id=\"56d5578\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-e-type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"button.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-button-wrapper\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<a class=\"elementor-button elementor-button-link elementor-size-sm\" href=\"tel:8778876372\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class=\"elementor-button-content-wrapper\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span class=\"elementor-bu